<common-name datatype='string'>fimB</common-name>
<comment datatype='string'>ppGpp, DksA, and GreA are non-DNA-binding regulatory molecules which control positively the transcription of  &lt;i&gt;fimB&lt;/i&gt;p2  expression through binding to RNAP. DksA and ppGpp stimulate transcription from the &lt;i&gt;fimB&lt;/i&gt;p2 promoter both independently and codependently [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/18284577&quot;&gt;Aberg08&lt;/a&gt;].
&lt;p&gt;
Baljinder et al. showed that NanR, NagC, and IHF activate &lt;i&gt;fimB&lt;/i&gt; gene expression, but they could not determine which of the three promoters (&lt;i&gt;fimB&lt;/i&gt;p1, &lt;i&gt;fimB&lt;/i&gt;p2, or &lt;i&gt;fimB&lt;/i&gt;p3) is affected [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17238917&quot;&gt;Sohanpal07&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15534208&quot;&gt;Sohanpal04&lt;/a&gt;], and none could demonstrate which is the transcription activation mechanism. They concluded that the activation from NagC and IHF could be indirect, altering the DNA structure of the intergenic region between &lt;i&gt;fimB&lt;/i&gt; and &lt;i&gt;nanC&lt;/i&gt;. Another possibility for system activation is through direct contact of NagC with RNA polymerase [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/17238917&quot;&gt;Sohanpal07&lt;/a&gt;, &lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/15534208&quot;&gt;Sohanpal04&lt;/a&gt;]. 
&lt;p&gt;
There are three potential transcription start sites. Transcription starting from two of these sites (P1 and P2) would  produce a similar-sized mRNA  to the one of &lt;i&gt;fimB&lt;/i&gt;, previously detected by Northern blot hybridizations.
&lt;p&gt;
Transcription of the genes &lt;i&gt;fimA&lt;/i&gt;, &lt;i&gt;fimB&lt;/i&gt;, and &lt;i&gt;fimE&lt;/i&gt; appears to be indirectly repressed by the protein GadE under low pH. The proteins GadW and GadX and also CRP seem to regulate the three &lt;i&gt;fim&lt;/i&gt; genes, but it has not been determined if this regulation is direct [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/35316170&quot;&gt;Schwan22&lt;/a&gt;]. During stationary phase, RpoS causes a negative effect on transcription of the &lt;i&gt;fimA&lt;/i&gt; and &lt;i&gt;fimB&lt;/i&gt; genes but not &lt;i&gt;fimE&lt;/i&gt; [&lt;a href=&quot;http://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pubmed/35316170&quot;&gt;Schwan22&lt;/a&gt;].</comment>
